07221nam a22015015i 9780691242576DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912425767 a10.1515/97806912425762doi  a(DE-B1597)635862  a(OCoLC)1369068609  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aBUS0690002bisacsh04a303.38223//eng/20230207eng  aMS 47602rvk0(DE-625)rvk/123715:1 aMorson, Gary Saul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMinds Wide Shut :bHow the New Fundamentalisms Divide Us /cGary Saul Morson, Morton Schapiro. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface to the Paper back Edition -- tPreface: Toward Dialogue -- t1 Fundamentalism Writ Large -- t2 Fundamentalism and Its Alternatives: From Fanaticism to Dialogue -- t3 Divided We Stand: The Politics of Hate -- t4 Price and Prejudice: Economics and the Quest for Truth -- t5 Searching for Eternal Truths: Religion and Its Discontents -- t6 Literature: How to Ruin It and Why You Shouldn’t -- t7 A Path Forward -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA timely exploration of intellectual dogmatism in politics, economics, religion, and literature—and what can be done to fight itPolarization may be pushing democracy to the breaking point. But few have explored the larger, interconnected forces that have set the stage for this crisis: namely, a rise in styles of thought, across a range of fields, that literary scholar Gary Saul Morson and economist Morton Schapiro call “fundamentalist.” In Minds Wide Shut, Morson and Schapiro examine how rigid adherence to ideological thinking has altered politics, economics, religion, and literature in ways that are mutually reinforcing and antithetical to the open-mindedness and readiness to compromise that animate democracy. In response, they propose alternatives that would again make serious dialogue possible.Fundamentalist thinking, Morson and Schapiro argue, is not limited to any one camp. It flourishes across the political spectrum, giving rise to dueling monologues of shouting and abuse between those who are certain that they can’t be wrong, that truth and justice are all on their side, and that there is nothing to learn from their opponents, who must be evil or deluded. But things don’t have to be this way. Drawing on thinkers and writers from across the humanities and social sciences, Morson and Schapiro show how we might begin to return to meaningful dialogue through case-based reasoning, objective analyses, lessons drawn from literature, and more.The result is a powerful invitation to leave behind simplification, rigidity, and extremism—and to move toward a future of greater open-mindedness, moderation, and, perhaps, even wisdom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aExtremists. 0aIdeology and literature. 0aIdeology. 0aPolarization (Social sciences). 0aReligious fundamentalism. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh  aAlternatives.  aAnton Chekhov.  aAtheism.  aCalvin (Calvin and Hobbes).  aCapitalism.  aCasuistry.  aCertainty.  aChristian fundamentalism.  aChristian.  aChristianity.  aClimate change.  aCognitive bias.  aCriticism.  aDarwinism.  aDialectical materialism.  aDialogic.  aEconomics.  aEconomist.  aEthical dilemma.  aEthics.  aEugenics.  aExplanation.  aFacebook.  aFalsity.  aFanaticism.  aFree trade.  aFreedom of speech.  aGary Saul Morson.  aGood and evil.  aHatred.  aHistorical criticism.  aHuman behavior.  aIdeology.  aIrony.  aIrrationality.